04310nam a22006375i 9780271072746DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20211992pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710727467 a10.1515/97802710727462doi  a(DE-B1597)584072  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBX7260.E3 7aREL0670802bisacsh04a261.8/0922201 aMcDermott, Gerald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOne Holy and Happy Society :bThe Public Theology of Jonathan Edwards /cGerald McDermott. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. God's Manner with a Covenant People: The National Covenant -- t2. That Glorious Work of God and the Beautiful Society: The Premillennial Age and the Millennium -- t3. Private Affection and Publick Spirit: The Edwardsean Social Ethic -- t4. The Importance and Functions of Strong Rods: Edwards on the Magistracy -- t5. The Priviledges and Duties of Subjects: A Theology of Citizenship -- t6. In Retrospect -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJonathan Edwards (1703-58) was arguably this country's greatest theologian and its finest philosopher before the nineteenth century. His school if disciples (the ";New Divinity";) exerted enormous influence on the religious and political cultures of late colonial and early republican America. Hence any study of religion and politics in early America must take account of this theologian and his legacy.Yet historians still regard Edward's social theory as either nonexistent or underdeveloped. Gerald McDermott demonstrates, to the contrary, that Edwards was very interested in the social and political affairs of his day, and commented upon them at length in his unpublished sermons and private notebooks. McDermott shows that Edwards thought deeply about New England's status under God, America's role in the millennium, the nature and usefulness of patriotism, the duties of a good magistrate, and what it means to be a good citizen. In fact, his sociopolitical theory was at least as fully developed as that of his better-known contemporaries and more progressive in its attitude toward citizens' rights.Using unpublished manuscripts that have previously been largely ignored, McDermott also convincingly challenges generations of scholarly opinion about Edwards. The Edwards who emerges from this nook is both less provincial and more this-worldly than the persona he is commonly given.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aPublic theologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271072746zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271072746423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271072746.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK